From 56059fd16a7625bf6b5cf2e53a15f581788af77f Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Lutz Fiebach <lfiebach@googlemail.com>
Date: Sat, 18 Jul 2026 12:10:07 +0200
Subject: [PATCH] onvif: per-profile FrameRateLimit/BitrateLimit from config

The VideoEncoder responses hardcoded <tt:FrameRateLimit>30</tt:FrameRateLimit>
and <tt:BitrateLimit>5000</tt:BitrateLimit> in the XML templates, so ONVIF
clients always saw 30 fps / 5000 kbps regardless of the encoder's real
settings (the RTSP stream itself is correct).

Make both driven by two new optional per-profile config keys, "framerate" and
"bitrate", read in conf.c. Profiles are pre-initialised to 30 / 5000 and
get_int_from_json() only overwrites when the key is present, so any existing
configuration that does not set them produces byte-identical output to before.
The values are threaded into every cat() call that renders an affected
template (single profiles use %FRAMERATE%/%BITRATE%, the dual-encoder _both
and _high templates use the _HIGH/_LOW variants).

No behavioural change for streamers that don't emit the keys; streamers that
write profiles.<name>.framerate/.bitrate into the ONVIF config now advertise
their real rates.
